Incident Management and Application Access MODULE 1 Tasks
1.1 Set Up New HR users
Lesson
A User is an individual who has been granted access to your ServiceNow instance. Each user is identified by a unique User ID, which serves as their login credential for the platform. Users are the foundation of access control and are assigned roles and permissions based on their responsibilities.
 Scenario
You are a ServiceNow administrator supporting the HR department. Your HR manager has requested that you create two new user accounts for members of the HR technical support team: Bob and Jane. Both will be providing technical support for HR systems and need access to the ServiceNow platform.

Task Objective
1. Create two new users in ServiceNow with the following information:
User 1:
User ID: Bob.HR_Support
First Name: Bob
Last Name: HR Support
Department: HR
Email: Bob@example.com
Active Checkbox: Enabled

User 2:
User ID: Jane.HR_Support
First Name: Jane
Last Name: HR Support
Department: HR
Email: Jane@example.com
Active Checkbox: Enabled
After creating both users, verify they appear in the Users list.

1.2.Create An HR favorite
Lesson
Groups are a collection of users who share a common purpose or perform similar tasks. Groups are used to streamline access management by assigning permissions collectively rather than individually. Common use cases for groups include approving change requests, resolving incidents, receiving email notifications, or managing the Service Catalog. Users are typically assigned to one or more groups, forming a hierarchical structure where groups define shared access and responsibilities.
 
Scenario
You are a ServiceNow administrator who frequently works with HR-related groups to manage access permissions and assignments. To improve your efficiency, you need to create a quick way to access all groups associated with the HR department. These groups might be named differently across your organization&mdash;some may contain "HR" while others use the full term "Human Resources."
Task Objective
Create and save a favorite that displays all groups containing "HR" or "Human Resources" in their name.

Filter Requirements:

- Show groups where the Name contains "HR

- Select the "OR" operator

- Show groups where the Name contains "Human Resources"

 

Favorite settings: 

- Select "Run" to apply your filter

- Add it to your favorites using the star icon in the filter pill or "Create favorite" from the hamburger menu.

- Name: HR Groups

1.3.Add users To HR Groups
Lesson
Groups in ServiceNow are collections of users who share common responsibilities or access requirements. They're fundamental for organizing teams, managing assignments, and controlling access to different parts of the Platform.

Groups become especially powerful when combined with assignment rules, access controls, and service catalog visibility - they're the foundation of proper user organization in ServiceNow.

Scenario
You are a ServiceNow administrator managing access for the HR department. Two new HR technical support team members, Bob HR Support and Jane HR Support, have just been onboarded and need access to handle payroll cases and general HR tier 1 support tickets. To grant them the appropriate permissions, you need to add both users to the HR Payroll and HR Tier 1 groups. If the groups do not exist, create them.

Task Objectives
1. Add Bob HR Support and Jane HR Support to the following groups:

- HR Payroll
- HR Tier 1

2. After adding both users to both groups, verify that the group memberships are correctly reflected in the instance.

1.4.Configure Impersonating Access For HR
Lesson
Impersonation allows administrators to log in as another user to see exactly what that user sees in ServiceNow. This is essential for troubleshooting access issues, testing configurations, and validating user experiences without needing the actual user's credentials.

Why Use Impersonation?

Troubleshoot access problems - See exactly what a user can and cannot access.
Test role configurations - Verify that roles provide the correct permissions.
Validate personalized settings - Check homepages, dashboards, and UI customizations.
Reproduce reported issues - Experience problems from the user's perspective.
Quality assurance - Test new features as different user types before deployment.
Scenario
You are a ServiceNow System Administrator responsible for the HR application. Bob HR Support and Jane HR Support are senior members of your HR technical team who need the ability to impersonate other users for troubleshooting and testing purposes. Because HR data is extremely sensitive and protected by various laws, users must have both the sn_hr_core.admin role and the impersonator role to impersonate users and view HR data.

Task Objective
Configure impersonation access for Bob HR Support and Jane HR Support:

1. Add the impersonator role to the HR Admin group.

2. Add Bob HR Support and Jane HR Support as members of the HR Admin group.

3. Verify that Jane HR Support has inherited the sn_hr_core.admin and impersonator roles through her group membership.

